{"TopicId":207655,"ForumId":44,"TopicTitle":"Science News Thread (for articles that don\u0026#039;t relate to ongoing discussions)","CreatedByName":"JoeSchmuckatelli","CreatedById":154477,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-04-09T14:54:26Z","PageNum":9,"Articles":[{"CreatedByName":"JoeSchmuckatelli","CreatedById":154477,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-08-04T12:01:40Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.cnn.com/2022/08/03/world/tonga-eruption-water-climate-stratosphere-scn/index.html\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://www.cnn.com/2022/08/03/world/tonga-eruption-water-climate-stratosphere-scn/index.html\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nBuncha new water in the atmosphere.\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\nQuote\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cspan style=\u0022background-color:#fefefe;color:#262626;font-size:18px;\u0022\u003EThey estimate that the eruption delivered 146 teragrams of water to the stratosphere. One teragram is the equivalent of a trillion grams, and in this case, it was equal to 10% of the water already present in the stratosphere.\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"StrandedonEarth","CreatedById":89439,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-08-13T03:09:10Z","Content":"\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsEmbeddedOther\u0022\u003E\n\u003Ciframe allowfullscreen=\u0022\u0022 data-controller=\u0022core.front.core.autosizeiframe\u0022 data-embedid=\u0022embed2161038087\u0022 scrolling=\u0022no\u0022 src=\u0022https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?app=core\u0026amp;module=system\u0026amp;controller=embed\u0026amp;url=https://twitter.com/wonderofscience/status/1558083381027409920?s=21%26t=AM0SDqnxHkz9NmlztoihKw\u0022 style=\u0022height:509px;\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"JoeSchmuckatelli","CreatedById":154477,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-08-13T04:38:36Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00224163381\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022207655\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221660360150\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u002289439\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022StrandedonEarth\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n1 hour ago, StrandedonEarth said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsEmbeddedOther\u0022\u003E\n\u003Ciframe allowfullscreen=\u0022\u0022 data-controller=\u0022core.front.core.autosizeiframe\u0022 data-embedid=\u0022embed2134088135\u0022 scrolling=\u0022no\u0022 src=\u0022https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?app=core\u0026amp;module=system\u0026amp;controller=embed\u0026amp;url=https://twitter.com/wonderofscience/status/1558083381027409920?s=21%26t=AM0SDqnxHkz9NmlztoihKw\u0022 style=\u0022height:775px;\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSo - what was it?\u00A0 A potassium (k-type?) asteroid, or something like this:\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022http://www.psrd.hawaii.edu/Nov99/PurpleSalt.html#:~:text=The%20decorative%20purple%20color%20(some,included%20in%20the%20sodium%20chloride.\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003EPSR Discoveries: Purple Salt and Tiny Drops of Water in Meteorites. (hawaii.edu)\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n(Cosmic rays, maaan)\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"kerbiloid","CreatedById":129408,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-08-13T05:20:18Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00224163396\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022207655\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221660365516\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022154477\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022JoeSchmuckatelli\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n38 minutes ago, JoeSchmuckatelli said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSo - what was it?\u00A0 A potassium (k-type?) asteroid, or something like this:\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022http://www.psrd.hawaii.edu/Nov99/PurpleSalt.html#:~:text=The%20decorative%20purple%20color%20(some,included%20in%20the%20sodium%20chloride.\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003EPSR Discoveries: Purple Salt and Tiny Drops of Water in Meteorites. (hawaii.edu)\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSomebody forgot to switch from CMYK to RGB in camera settings.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222022-08-13T05:20:29Z\u0022 title=\u002208/13/2022 05:20  AM\u0022 data-short=\u00221 yr\u0022\u003EAugust 13, 2022\u003C/time\u003E by kerbiloid\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"JoeSchmuckatelli","CreatedById":154477,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-08-13T14:20:54Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00224163412\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022207655\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221660368018\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022129408\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022kerbiloid\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n8 hours ago, kerbiloid said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSomebody forgot to switch from CMYK to RGB in camera settings.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsEmbeddedVideo\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv\u003E\n\u003Ciframe allowfullscreen=\u0022\u0022 frameborder=\u00220\u0022 height=\u0022150\u0022 src=\u0022https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/4xEEkruL75U?feature=oembed\u0022 title=\u0022Raspberry Sound Effects\u0022 width=\u0022200\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"JoeSchmuckatelli","CreatedById":154477,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-08-17T12:12:52Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://slate.com/technology/2022/08/nasa-uranus-probe-orbiter-lol-sorry.html\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://slate.com/technology/2022/08/nasa-uranus-probe-orbiter-lol-sorry.html\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\nQuote\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u0022... it\u2019s not so much of a challenge to segue into something like \u2018\u003Cstrong\u003Edid you know Uranus smells of farts\u003C/strong\u003E?\u2019 (which it does), which will make people laugh, but now you\u2019re talking about atmospheric composition.\u201D\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"JoeSchmuckatelli","CreatedById":154477,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-08-26T12:35:43Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nNot sure if this is science - or just someone having fun with technology in the sciences...\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nBasically, here are a bunch of photos of parts of our galaxy and other astronomical phenomena where the image is translated into music (well sound).\u00A0 Note: not \u003Cem\u003Eset\u003C/em\u003E to music... The image data is converted to sound.\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsEmbeddedVideo\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv\u003E\n\u003Ciframe allowfullscreen=\u0022\u0022 frameborder=\u00220\u0022 height=\u0022150\u0022 src=\u0022https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/ayAYDVvjs_E?feature=oembed\u0022 title=\u0022Data Sonification: M16 (Eagle Nebula,\u0022 width=\u0022200\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n...except that they also try to make the images even more musical, which feels \u0027artistic\u0027.\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsEmbeddedVideo\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv\u003E\n\u003Ciframe allowfullscreen=\u0022\u0022 frameborder=\u00220\u0022 height=\u0022113\u0022 src=\u0022https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/9YIERCD5PYY?feature=oembed\u0022 title=\u0022Data Sonification: Galactic Center (Multiwavelength)\u0022 width=\u0022200\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI find all this both compelling... And a little odd...\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsEmbeddedVideo\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv\u003E\n\u003Ciframe allowfullscreen=\u0022\u0022 frameborder=\u00220\u0022 height=\u0022150\u0022 src=\u0022https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/Ph_-9awNGp0?feature=oembed\u0022 title=\u0022Data Sonification: Cat\u0027s Eye Nebula (NGC 6543) Multiwavelength\u0022 width=\u0022200\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThere is a whole site:\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://chandra.si.edu/sound/index.html#crab\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://chandra.si.edu/sound/index.html#crab\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222022-08-26T12:36:31Z\u0022 title=\u002208/26/2022 12:36  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00221 yr\u0022\u003EAugust 26, 2022\u003C/time\u003E by JoeSchmuckatelli\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"JoeSchmuckatelli","CreatedById":154477,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-08-26T16:55:54Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nNot to be outdone:\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nDoppelganger epigenetics explains differences in unrelated people who share genes.\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.cnn.com/2022/08/25/health/doppelganger-dna-study-wellness/index.html\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://www.cnn.com/2022/08/25/health/doppelganger-dna-study-wellness/index.html\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cspan\u003E\u00A0\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u002220220825-09-dna-study-melissa-thorkilsen\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 data-ratio=\u0022154.50\u0022 height=\u00221200\u0022 width=\u00221200\u0022 src=\u0022https://www.cnn.com/interactive/uploads/20220825-09-dna-study-melissa-thorkilsen-andrea-chalon-restricted.jpg\u0022\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThese women are not related\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u002220220825-01-dna-study-pierre-rondou-cami\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 data-ratio=\u0022154.50\u0022 height=\u00221200\u0022 width=\u00221200\u0022 src=\u0022https://www.cnn.com/interactive/uploads/20220825-01-dna-study-pierre-rondou-camille-dube-2-restricted.jpg\u0022\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cspan\u003ENeither are these men\u00A0\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cdiv style=\u0022background-color:#fefefe;color:#262626;font-size:1.2rem;padding:0px 10px;\u0022\u003E\n\u0022... scientists think they can explain what it is that makes them look so similar -- and could explain why each of us may have doppelg\u00E4nger.\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv style=\u0022background-color:#fefefe;color:#262626;font-size:1.2rem;padding:0px 10px;\u0022\u003E\nPeople who resemble each other, but are not directly related, still seem to have genetic similarities, according to a new study.\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv style=\u0022background-color:#fefefe;color:#262626;font-size:15px;\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv style=\u0022color:#262626;font-size:1.2rem;padding:0px 10px;\u0022\u003E\nAmong those who had these genetic similarities, many also had similar weights, similar lifestyle factors, and similar behavioral traits like smoking and education levels. That could mean that genetic variation is related to physical appearance and also, potentially may influence some habits and behavior.\u0022\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222022-08-26T17:01:14Z\u0022 title=\u002208/26/2022 05:01  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00221 yr\u0022\u003EAugust 26, 2022\u003C/time\u003E by JoeSchmuckatelli\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"JoeSchmuckatelli","CreatedById":154477,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-08-26T20:25:58Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nWaterworld - now, not just a movie!\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.cbsnews.com/news/water-world-exoplanet-toi-1452-b-tess-james-webb-space-telescope/\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://www.cbsnews.com/news/water-world-exoplanet-toi-1452-b-tess-james-webb-space-telescope/\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022fa9dui9x0aaeys9.jpg\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 data-ratio=\u002271.17\u0022 height=\u0022800\u0022 width=\u00221200\u0022 src=\u0022https://assets3.cbsnewsstatic.com/hub/i/r/2022/08/26/7d0ecf37-f235-437d-8ce9-150039f83023/thumbnail/1280x854/730d2e7919c04e29ce0319c84777e8a3/fa9dui9x0aaeys9.jpg\u0022\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"kerbiloid","CreatedById":129408,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-08-26T20:30:28Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00224167559\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022207655\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221661532954\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022154477\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022JoeSchmuckatelli\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n3 hours ago, JoeSchmuckatelli said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nand could explain why each of us may have doppelg\u00E4nger.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI had two of them. One in school, two years older, another one in the university.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"StrandedonEarth","CreatedById":89439,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-08-28T16:44:22Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nBest picture I\u0027ve seen of lunar \u0022pits\u0022 - possibly openings into ancient lava tubes...\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022m126710873re_map_thumb_0.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 data-ratio=\u0022100.00\u0022 height=\u0022800\u0022 width=\u0022800\u0022 src=\u0022https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/m126710873re_map_thumb_0.png\u0022\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nFrom:\u00A0\u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2022/08/lro-surface-pit-temperatures/\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2022/08/lro-surface-pit-temperatures/\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"JoeSchmuckatelli","CreatedById":154477,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-08-30T17:32:36Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIn a boon to those of us who enjoy reading science articles:\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\nQuote\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cspan style=\u0022background-color:#ffffff;color:#262626;font-size:18px;text-align:left;\u0022\u003Ecritics of paywalls argue that they obstruct the free flow of information, have enabled price gouging by some publishers, and force U.S. taxpayers to \u201Cpay twice\u201D\u2014once to fund the research and again to see the results. Since the late 1990s, the critics have lobbied Congress and the White House to require free and immediate \u201Copen access\u201D to government-funded research.\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cspan style=\u0022background-color:#ffffff;color:#262626;font-size:18px;text-align:left;\u0022\u003E...\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cspan style=\u0022background-color:#ffffff;color:#262626;font-size:18px;text-align:left;\u0022\u003EThe new policy reflects the profound changes that have rocked academic publishing since the U.S. public access debate began in earnest more than 25 years ago. Then, subscription-based print journals were the primary means of disseminating research results, and publishers fiercely resisted any policy change that threatened an often highly profitable business model. But pressure from university libraries tired of paying rising subscription fees, and patient groups angry about having to pay to read taxpayer-funded biomedical studies, helped catalyze serious discussion of policy change. At the same time, the rise of the internet fueled publishing experiments, such as open-access journals and the posting of freely accessible \u201Cpreprints\u201D that have not been peer reviewed.\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.science.org/content/article/white-house-requires-immediate-public-access-all-u-s--funded-research-papers-2025\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003EWhite House requires immediate public access to all U.S.-funded research papers by 2025 | Science | AAAS\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"DDE","CreatedById":146349,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-08-30T17:50:05Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00224168972\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022207655\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221661880756\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022154477\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022JoeSchmuckatelli\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n13 minutes ago, JoeSchmuckatelli said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIn a boon to those of us who enjoy reading science articles:\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.science.org/content/article/white-house-requires-immediate-public-access-all-u-s--funded-research-papers-2025\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003EWhite House requires immediate public access to all U.S.-funded research papers by 2025 | Science | AAAS\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cspan\u003E...but that would mean siding with \u003Ca href=\u0022https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexandra_Elbakyan\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003EElbakyan\u003C/a\u003E. Which is probably going to go as swimmingly as the Saule Omarova confirmation hearings.\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"JoeSchmuckatelli","CreatedById":154477,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-08-30T18:07:33Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00224168981\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022207655\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221661881805\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022146349\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022DDE\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n19 minutes ago, DDE said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cspan\u003E...but that would mean siding with \u003Ca href=\u0022https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexandra_Elbakyan\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003EElbakyan\u003C/a\u003E. Which is probably going to go as swimmingly as the Saule Omarova confirmation hearings.\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nInteresting - I did not know the back story of that site until seeing the wiki.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n(There\u0027s been some creative writing there, btw: I would not compare her to Snowden.\u00A0 Perhaps Sean Parker would be more apt.\u00A0 Snowden should be compared to people like Yurchenko.)\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222022-08-30T18:09:10Z\u0022 title=\u002208/30/2022 06:09  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00221 yr\u0022\u003EAugust 30, 2022\u003C/time\u003E by JoeSchmuckatelli\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"kerbiloid","CreatedById":129408,"CreatedDateTime":"2022-08-31T04:09:14Z","Content":"\n\